children.name: Client Side Form Val
children.characters: Client Side Form Validation : Field States

children.name: When a field is no l
children.characters: When a field is no longer selected to data entry is on blure. The above example contains a text value but is no longer selected for data entry.

children.name: When a field has bee
children.characters: When a field has been selected for input it is in focus. This styling is left completely to the browser to determine and should not be custom styled. The visual representation above is a common example and not a guideline.

children.name: Minimum of 1 chartac
children.characters: Minimum of 1 chartacter. Maximum of 25 characters. Cannot contain special characters.

children.name: When a field fails t
children.characters:
When a field fails to meet the set validation rules after data entry it is considered to be errored or in error. Note that the reasons for failure are stacked beneath the field. This forces the fields below to move vertically.

As error fields are resolved they return to an OnBlur state.

children.name: Must be between 8-12
children.characters: Must be between 8-12 characters. Must contain at least 1 number, 1 letter, and 1 special character.

children.name: When a field enforce
children.characters: When a field enforces a particular input format it is called a requirement for that field. We communicate those requirements with terse but detailed text under the target field.

children.name: A field appears on a
children.characters:
A field appears on a newly loaded form in a default state. This type of field is waiting for input.

Note the use of the placeholder attribute to denote the expected input.

children.name: When we say "client-
children.characters: When we say "client-side form validation," we mean checking a web form to make sure all the data are complete and correct before sending the form off to the server. All the checking is performed in the browser by JavaScript.
